@startuml
!include <C4/C4_Context>
!include <C4/C4_Container>
!include <C4/C4_Component>

/'
C3 – Component Diagram

Purpose:
Shows the internal structure of a single *Container by decomposing it into
*Components, their responsibilities, and the relationships between them.

Scope:
- Exactly one *Container from the C2 Container Diagram
- The container is treated as the system boundary at this level

*Container:
- The container being decomposed (e.g., API, backend service, web application)

*Components:
- Components within the container, each representing a cohesive unit of
  functionality with a well-defined responsibility and interface
  (e.g., controllers, services, repositories)

*Relationships:
- Component -> Component: Interactions within the container
- Component -> External Software System: Calls made directly from the container
- Component -> Container (external): Calls to other containers, when relevant

Design Notes:
- This diagram captures the internal design and structure of a container
- Design patterns and architectural patterns may be shown where they help
  explain responsibility, direction of dependencies, or extensibility
  (e.g., MVC, layered architecture, hexagonal / ports and adapters, CQRS)
- Components should be coarse-grained and meaningful; avoid modeling
  classes, utilities, or framework internals
- Cross-cutting concerns (e.g., logging, security) may be implied rather
  than explicitly shown
- Class-level design and detailed implementation belong to the Code (C4) level
'/

Container_Boundary(api_boundary, "API Service") {
    Component(recipe_controller, "Recipe Controller", "Handles HTTP requests.")
    Component(recipe_repository, "Recipe Repository", "Interacts with the Database.")
    Component(cdn_client, "CDN Client", "Uploads/manages images on the CDN.")
}

Rel(recipe_controller, recipe_repository, "Uses")
Rel(recipe_controller, cdn_client, "Uses")

@enduml

